<item>
 <title>Growing from Seed</title>
 <link>http://www.completelyeco.com/articles/growing-seed</link>
 <description>
&lt;div class=&quot;serif field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden clearfix&quot;&gt;
  
  &lt;!-- THIS SHOULD BE FOR JUST THE BODY --&gt;
  
  &lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;
          &lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;What is that saying about March…something about a lion?  This year, March is slinking in to the mid-Atlantic like a pussy cat, and as the thermometer consistently tops 60 degrees, gardeners are emerging from hibernation to ready their spaces for planting, perhaps a few weeks earlier than usual.  Peas, potatoes, and spinach can go in the ground mid-month, but the wise gardener will bide her time for a few more weeks to avoid losing other tender seedlings to late winter cold snaps.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Most people are familiar with the process of growing plants from seedlings: buy baby plant, place baby plant in ground or pot, dose regularly with water, sunlight, love.  Growing from seed is a slightly different story.  Some seeds prefer to be planted directly in the ground (roots, beans, peas), while others need to be grown to a transplantable size in the comfort of a greenhouse or light table (the slow-pokes: cabbages, broccoli, tomatoes, peppers, eggplant), still others can swing either way (lettuces, kale, squash).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is no shame in buying your seedlings--but as with most things of worth, the best transplants are those grown locally.  Many farmers sell veggie seedlings at the market alongside their spring crops.  These will be better adapted to regional disease and pest pressures than those grown in mysterious, faraway greenhouses.  Growing your own seedlings, on the other hand, requires a bit of infrastructure, but it is a galvanizing gardening experience.  Use seedling trays, or improvise with egg cartons or yogurt cups--just be sure to poke some drainage holes.  Use a good quality potting soil—perhaps one that is specifically for seed starting.  The fine texture of these specialty mixes will ensure that there is good contact between the seeds and the moist substrate.  Fill your chosen containers with pre-moistened potting soil: unless it includes a wetting agent, many potting mixes are naturally hydrophobic and need coaxing to soak up water.  Top watering dry mix will just let water run through to the drainage holes.   So remember your best mud pie recipe, dump your mix in a plastic bin, add water, and work it in with your hands or a trowel until it is evenly moist.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Consult seed packets for timing and depth information.  Always err on the side of planting shallow rather than deep; a seed planted too deeply will likely sprout, but run out of stored energy before reaching the surface, where it can start harvesting sunlight for energy.  For small seeded plants, the depth will be ¼-1/2 inch—really nothing more than a tiny dimple in the surface of your soil.  Drop in two seeds (three if your seeds are old).  Since germination is always less than 100%, adding an extra seed will ensure that you get at least one sprout, rather than sacrificing the space to a dud.  You’ll need to thin to one seedling per planting cell after seedlings are a few inches tall.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A little moisture and warmth is all that&#039;s needed to bring on germination.  Seedling mats, which heat trays from the bottom, can improve germination, but covering your trays with plastic to seal in moisture and placing on top of the fridge can have a similar effect (don’t try this with lettuces, which need light in order to germinate).  Check daily: once you see sprouts, your newly hatched babies will need plenty of light to keep the party going.  A south-facing window can do the job, but you&#039;ll have stronger, stouter seedlings if you grow them under florescent lights, hung right on top of them (seriously, right on top: 2 inches).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Feed seedlings with a diluted liquid fertilizer once a week or so.  Fish and kelp emulsions are readily available organic—albeit stinky—fertilizers appropriate for seedlings.  Follow package directions for dilution ratios.  Check moisture daily, but it’s okay to let the surface of the soil dry between waterings—this will promote strong root growth and discourage fungal growth.  Other than that, just be sure to talk to them in a sweet voice and play classical music when you’re away.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Before they head for the great outdoors, toughen your seedlings up for a week or so by treating them to increasing daily doses of outdoor sun and wind.  If you’re about the house, you can arrange a series of field trips outside, increasing in length each day.  If you’re out workin’ like a dog, put them out in different locations each morning, starting with least exposed part of your yard, and gradually moving them out into full sun and wind.  Bring them in each night, especially if the weather calls for freezing temps.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Witnessing the transformation of a seed into a mature plant is a tiny spring miracle.  Urban Farmhouse works with clients to help them witness this seasonal magic, and turn it into honest food.  See &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.urbanfarmhouseonline.com&quot;&gt;www.urbanfarmhouseonline.com&lt;/a&gt;, or contact &lt;a href=&quot;mailto:farmer@urbanfarmhouseonline.com&quot;&gt;farmer@urbanfarmhouseonline.com&lt;/a&gt; for information on our edible landscaping and gardening education services.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
